gov.usgs.edge.config

Class RequestType

  • java.lang.Object
    • gov.usgs.edge.config.RequestType

  • public final class RequestType
extends java.lang.Object
    RequestType.java If the name of the class does not match the name of the field in the class you may need to modify the rs.getSTring in the constructor. This RequestType templace for creating a database database object. It is not really needed by the RequestTypePanel which uses the DBObject system for changing a record in the database file. However, you have to have this shell to create objects containing a database record for passing around and manipulating. There are two constructors normally given:
    1) passed a result set positioned to the database record to decode
    2) Passed all of the data arguments needed to build the same set of data.
    The RequestType should be replaced with capitalized version (class name) for the file. requestType should be replaced with the lower case version (for variables). Both the constructors use the "makeRequestType(list of data args) to set the local variables to the value. The result set just uses the rs.get???("fieldname") to get the data from the database where the other passes the arguments from the caller.
    Notes on Enums :
    * data class should have code like :
    import java.util.ArrayList; /// Import for Enum manipulation
    .
    static ArrayList fieldEnum; // This list will have Strings corresponding to enum
    .
    .
    // To convert an enum we need to create the fieldEnum ArrayList. Do only once(static)
    if(fieldEnum == null) fieldEnum = FUtil.getEnum(databaseConnectionThread.getConnection("DATABASE"),"table","fieldName");

    // Get the int corresponding to an Enum String for storage in the data base and
    // the index into the JComboBox representing this Enum
    localVariable = FUtil.enumStringToInt(fieldEnum, enumString);
